message.content:
As a smart contract developer, I can inform you that it's impossible to derive the exact Solidity source code from the bytecode. Bytecode is the compiled version of the source code and converting it back to the source code will not be an exact process as comments, variable names and formatting will be lost. 

However, we can decompile the bytecode to EVM (Ethereum Virtual Machine) instructions using tools like Etherscan, but this will not give you back the original Solidity code. It will just provide a lower-level representation of the code which is not human friendly. 

For an accurate Solidity source code, one will need the original source code. It is a best practice to verify the source code on Etherscan so that it's publicly available and others can interact with the contract in a trustless manner.
